summary.dataset_description: A dataset containing 2D normal distribution data with two columns 'u' and 'v'.

goals.question: What is the correlation between 'u' and 'v' in the 2D normal distribution?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the relationship between the two coordinates and whether they are positively, negatively or not correlated.

goals.question: What is the distribution of 'u' in the 2D normal distribution?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the spread of the 'u' coordinate values and whether they follow a normal distribution.

goals.question: What is the distribution of 'v' in the 2D normal distribution?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the spread of the 'v' coordinate values and whether they follow a normal distribution.

goals.question: What is the joint distribution of 'u' and 'v' in the 2D normal distribution?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the joint distribution of the two coordinates and whether they follow a bivariate normal distribution.

goals.question: What is the mean and standard deviation of 'u' and 'v' in the 2D normal distribution?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the central tendency and variability of the two coordinates and whether they are similar or different in terms of their distribution properties.

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.scatterplot(data=data, x='u', y='v')
    plt.title("What is the correlation between 'u' and 'v' in the 2D normal distribution?", wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure()
    sns.histplot(data=data, x='u', kde=True, color='blue')
    median_u = data['u'].median()
    plt.axvline(median_u, color='red', linestyle='--', label=f"Median: {median_u:.2f}")
    plt.title("What is the distribution of 'u' in the 2D normal distribution?", wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure()
    sns.histplot(data=data, x='v', kde=True, color='blue')
    plt.axvline(data['v'].median(), color='red', linestyle='--', label=f"Median: {data['v'].median():.2f}")
    plt.title("What is the distribution of 'v' in the 2D normal distribution?", wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.histplot(data, x='u', y='v', bins=30, cmap='viridis', cbar=True)
    plt.title("What is the joint distribution of 'u' and 'v' in the 2D normal distribution?", wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    sns.boxplot(data=data, ax=ax)
    ax.set_title("What is the mean and standard deviation of 'u' and 'v' in the 2D normal distribution?", wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
